-- Corn, Soybeans Called to Open Higher on Hot, Dry Weather in U.S.
-- B y   P h o e b e   S e d g m a n
-- 2012-07-29T21:50:58Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-07-29/corn-soybeans-called-to-open-higher-on-hot-dry-weather-in-u-s-.html
What follows are opening calls for
U.S. grain and oilseed markets, which open on the Chicago Board
of Trade at 6 a.m. Singapore time.  -- Corn futures may open 2 cents to 3 cents a bushel higher on
the CBOT on forecasts of hot and dry conditions across most of
the U.S. Midwest in the near term, while some crops have already
been damaged by drought, said Ker Chung Yang, an analyst at
Phillip Futures Pte.  -- Soybean futures may open 4 cents to 5 cents a bushel higher
as continued drought in the U.S. threatens crops, he said in an
e-mail.  -- Wheat futures may open 2 cents to 3 cents a bushel higher on
concerns production in  Russia  may be lower than forecast after
dry weather and amid slow crop development in the U.K., he said.  To contact the reporter for this story: Phoebe Sedgman in
Melbourne at   psedgman2@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
